.TH KNETD.CONF 5 "2026-06-25" "knetd" "File Formats"
.SH NAME
knetd.conf \- configuration file for knetd daemon
.SH SYNOPSIS
.I /etc/knetd/knetd.conf
.SH DESCRIPTION
The
.B knetd.conf
file configures the knetd VPN daemon using TOML format. It defines daemon
behavior, VPN instances, network topology, and security settings.

.SH FILE FORMAT
The configuration uses TOML (Tom's Obvious Minimal Language) syntax. See
.I https://toml.io
for format details.

.SH GLOBAL SETTINGS
.TP
.B socket_path
Path to Unix domain socket for RPC (default: /run/knetd/knetd.sock)

.TP
.B log_level
Logging verbosity: trace, debug, info, warn, error (default: info)

.TP
.B colored_logs
Enable colored log output: true/false (default: false)

.TP
.B disable_privileged
Disable privileged mode even when running as root (default: false)

.TP
.B state_file
Path to persistent state file for crash recovery (optional)

.SH INSTANCE CONFIGURATION
Instances are defined in
.B [[instances]]
array tables. Each instance represents an independent VPN network.

.SS Instance Fields
.TP
.B name
Unique instance name (required, string)

.TP
.B auto_start
Automatically start instance on daemon startup (default: false)

.TP
.B full_mesh
Enable automatic full-mesh link creation between all nodes (default: false)

.SS Nodes
Nodes are defined in
.B [[instances.nodes]]
array tables.

.TP
.B host_id
Node's unique ID 1-65535 (required, integer)

.TP
.B name
Human-readable node name (required, string)

.TP
.B link_addresses
Array of addresses for full-mesh mode (e.g., ["10.0.0.1:5405", "10.1.0.1:5405"])

.SS Links (Manual Mode)
Links are defined in
.B [[instances.links]]
array tables when
.B full_mesh
is false.

.TP
.B link_id
Link ID 0-7 (required, integer)

.TP
.B from_host
Source host ID (required, integer)

.TP
.B to_host
Destination host ID (required, integer)

.TP
.B transport
Transport type: udp, sctp, loopback (required, string)

.TP
.B src_addr
Source address IP:PORT (required, string)

.TP
.B dst_addr
Destination address IP:PORT (optional for loopback, string)

.TP
.B auto_enable
Automatically enable link on startup (default: false)

.SS Nozzle (Tap Device)
Nozzle configuration in
.B [instances.nozzle]
table.

.TP
.B name
Tap device name (optional, generated if omitted)

.TP
.B ip_addresses
Array of IP addresses in CIDR notation (required, e.g., ["192.168.100.0/24"])
.RS
.PP
\fBIMPORTANT\fR: IP addresses are treated as \fIbase addresses\fR. The daemon
automatically embeds the node ID into the host bits to ensure uniqueness across
all nodes. For example, with base IP 192.168.100.0/24:
.IP \(bu 2
Node 1 gets 192.168.100.1/24
.IP \(bu
Node 2 gets 192.168.100.2/24
.IP \(bu
Node 3 gets 192.168.100.3/24
.PP
This allows the same config to be deployed to all nodes.
.RE

.TP
.B mac
Base MAC address (optional, e.g., "fe:54:00:00")
.RS
.PP
\fBIMPORTANT\fR: The MAC address is treated as a \fIbase address\fR. The daemon
automatically replaces the last 2 bytes with the node ID. For example:
.IP \(bu 2
Base MAC: fe:54:00:00
.IP \(bu
Node 1: fe:54:00:00:00:01
.IP \(bu
Node 2: fe:54:00:00:00:02
.RE

.TP
.B mtu
Maximum transmission unit in bytes (optional, integer)

.TP
.B updown_path
Directory containing up/down scripts (optional, string)

.TP
.B auto_up
Bring device up immediately (default: false)

.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Minimal Configuration
.EX
socket_path = "/run/knetd/knetd.sock"
log_level = "info"

[[instances]]
name = "vpn1"
.EE

.SS Full-Mesh Cluster (Corosync-Style)
.EX
socket_path = "/run/knetd/knetd.sock"
log_level = "info"
state_file = "/var/lib/knetd/state.json"

[[instances]]
name = "ha-cluster"
auto_start = true
full_mesh = true

[[instances.nodes]]
host_id = 1
name = "node1"
link_addresses = ["192.168.1.1:5405", "10.0.0.1:5405"]

[[instances.nodes]]
host_id = 2
name = "node2"
link_addresses = ["192.168.1.2:5405", "10.0.0.2:5405"]

[[instances.nodes]]
host_id = 3
name = "node3"
link_addresses = ["192.168.1.3:5405", "10.0.0.3:5405"]

[instances.nozzle]
name = "knet0"
ip_addresses = ["192.168.100.0/24"]
mac = "fe:54:00:00"
mtu = 1400
auto_up = true
.EE

Deploy to all nodes:
.EX
# Node 1
knetd --node-id 1 --config /etc/knetd/cluster.conf

# Node 2
knetd --node-id 2 --config /etc/knetd/cluster.conf

# Node 3
knetd --node-id 3 --config /etc/knetd/cluster.conf
.EE

Each node automatically gets unique MAC/IP:
.IP \(bu 2
Node 1: MAC fe:54:00:00:00:01, IP 192.168.100.1/24
.IP \(bu
Node 2: MAC fe:54:00:00:00:02, IP 192.168.100.2/24
.IP \(bu
Node 3: MAC fe:54:00:00:00:03, IP 192.168.100.3/24

.SS Manual Link Configuration
.EX
[[instances]]
name = "custom-net"
auto_start = true

[[instances.nodes]]
host_id = 1
name = "node1"

[[instances.nodes]]
host_id = 2
name = "node2"

# Link from node 1 to node 2
[[instances.links]]
link_id = 0
from_host = 1
to_host = 2
transport = "udp"
src_addr = "10.0.0.1:5000"
dst_addr = "10.0.0.2:5000"
auto_enable = true

# Redundant link
[[instances.links]]
link_id = 1
from_host = 1
to_host = 2
transport = "udp"
src_addr = "10.1.0.1:5000"
dst_addr = "10.1.0.2:5000"
auto_enable = true
.EE

.SH NODE-AGNOSTIC CONFIGURATION
The configuration file is designed to be \fInode-agnostic\fR \- the same file
can be deployed to all nodes in a cluster. Each node identifies itself via:
.IP 1. 4
\fB\-\-node\-id\fR command-line argument
.IP 2.
\fBKNETD_NODE_ID\fR environment variable

When the daemon starts, it:
.IP \(bu 2
Finds the node with matching host_id in the config
.IP \(bu
Creates instances with that node's host_id
.IP \(bu
Adds all other nodes as remote hosts
.IP \(bu
Only configures links where from_host matches the local node

.SH NOZZLE UNIQUE ADDRESSING
When using nozzle (tap) devices, MAC and IP addresses are automatically
made unique per node:

.SS MAC Address
The configured MAC is a \fIbase address\fR. The last 2 bytes are replaced
with the node ID:
.IP \(bu 2
Base: fe:54:00:00 (first 4 bytes)
.IP \(bu
Node 1: fe:54:00:00:00:01
.IP \(bu
Node 256: fe:54:00:00:01:00

.SS IPv4 Address
The configured IP is masked and combined with the node ID:
.IP \(bu 2
Base: 192.168.100.0/24
.IP \(bu
Prefix /24 leaves 8 bits for node ID
.IP \(bu
Node 1: 192.168.100.1
.IP \(bu
Node 254: 192.168.100.254

.SS IPv6 Address
The node ID is appended as hex after ::
.IP \(bu 2
Base: fd00::/64
.IP \(bu
Node 1: fd00::1
.IP \(bu
Node 256: fd00::100

See
.I /usr/share/doc/knetd/NOZZLE_UNIQUE_ADDRESSING.md
for details.

.SH FILES
.TP
.I /etc/knetd/knetd.conf
Default configuration file

.TP
.I /var/lib/knetd/state.json
Persistent state (if state_file configured)

